<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="127" pageId="9" pageNumber="126" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[794,1399,425,2081]" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[794,951,425,449]" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">Redescription</emphasis>
: Body length 7.0 mm; length of forebody 
<quantity box="[794,879,457,481]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" pageId="9" pageNumber="126" unit="mm" value="3.3">3.3 mm</quantity>
. Coloration (note that the 
<typeStatus box="[1185,1280,457,481]" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">holotype</typeStatus>
is teneral; mature specimens are most likely of significantly darker coloration) (
<figureCitation box="[935,1003,521,545]" captionStart="Figs 1–41" captionStartId="45.[151,191,1956,1978]" captionTargetBox="[152,1389,232,1855]" captionTargetId="figure-203@45.[151,1398,232,1874]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Figs 1–41:Antennae of Zyrasspp.:kraatzi(1),exasperatus(2),pindarae (3–5),perforatus(6),championi(7),pallipes (8),condignus (9), nitens (10), truncatus (11), nilgiriensis (12), hirsutiventris (13), russiceps (14), brignolii (15), hastatus (16), parageminus (17–18), latilobatus (19), alternans (20), hirtus (21), nigroaeneus (22), luteipes (23), longilobatus (24), morvani (25), gratellus (Malaysia) (26), castaneus, lectotype (27),proximus (28–29),novinversus (30–31), brevilobatus(32), parvicollis(33), ambulans (34),matangensis (35), densissimus (36), densihirtus (37), nigrihirtus (38), gratellus (Sulawesi) (39), gardneri (40), titan (41). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742367/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">Figs 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1020,1050,521,545]" captionStart="Figs 42–54" captionStartId="46.[189,229,2012,2034]" captionTargetBox="[191,1436,232,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-109@46.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figs 42–54: Forebody of Zyras spp.: kraatzi (42), exasperatus (43), pindarae (44), perforatus (45), championi (46), pallipes (47), condignus, holotype (48), condignus, Nepal (49), nigroaeneus (50), morvani (51), truncatus (52), longilobatus (53), hastatus (54). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742371/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">43</figureCitation>
): head dark-brown; pronotum and elytra brown, with the postero-lateral portions of the elytra slightly and diffusely darker; abdomen: tergites II–VI brown with paler posterior margins and paratergites, tergites VII–X reddish; legs yellowishbrown; antennae dark-brown with antennomere XI reddish-brown; maxillary palpi brown, with the apical palpomere yellowish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[794,1399,425,2081]" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[873,947,777,801]" captionStart="Figs 42–54" captionStartId="46.[189,229,2012,2034]" captionTargetBox="[191,1436,232,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-109@46.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figs 42–54: Forebody of Zyras spp.: kraatzi (42), exasperatus (43), pindarae (44), perforatus (45), championi (46), pallipes (47), condignus, holotype (48), condignus, Nepal (49), nigroaeneus (50), morvani (51), truncatus (52), longilobatus (53), hastatus (54). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742371/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">Fig. 43</figureCitation>
) distinctly transverse, broadly impunctate along middle; punctation in lateral dorsal portions moderately fine and moderately sparse. Eyes slightly longer than postocular region in dorsal view. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[801,863,905,929]" captionStart="Figs 1–41" captionStartId="45.[151,191,1956,1978]" captionTargetBox="[152,1389,232,1855]" captionTargetId="figure-203@45.[151,1398,232,1874]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Figs 1–41:Antennae of Zyrasspp.:kraatzi(1),exasperatus(2),pindarae (3–5),perforatus(6),championi(7),pallipes (8),condignus (9), nitens (10), truncatus (11), nilgiriensis (12), hirsutiventris (13), russiceps (14), brignolii (15), hastatus (16), parageminus (17–18), latilobatus (19), alternans (20), hirtus (21), nigroaeneus (22), luteipes (23), longilobatus (24), morvani (25), gratellus (Malaysia) (26), castaneus, lectotype (27),proximus (28–29),novinversus (30–31), brevilobatus(32), parvicollis(33), ambulans (34),matangensis (35), densissimus (36), densihirtus (37), nigrihirtus (38), gratellus (Sulawesi) (39), gardneri (40), titan (41). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742367/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[882,963,905,929]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="9" pageNumber="126" unit="mm" value="2.6">2.6 mm</quantity>
long and slender; antennomeres IV–V weakly oblong, VI–VII approximately as long as broad, VIII–X weakly transverse, X much less than 1.5 times as broad as long, and XI slightly longer than the combined length of IX and X.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[794,1399,425,2081]" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[917,991,1065,1089]" captionStart="Figs 42–54" captionStartId="46.[189,229,2012,2034]" captionTargetBox="[191,1436,232,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-109@46.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figs 42–54: Forebody of Zyras spp.: kraatzi (42), exasperatus (43), pindarae (44), perforatus (45), championi (46), pallipes (47), condignus, holotype (48), condignus, Nepal (49), nigroaeneus (50), morvani (51), truncatus (52), longilobatus (53), hastatus (54). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742371/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">Fig. 43</figureCitation>
) weakly transverse, 1.1 times as broad as long and 1.37 times as broad as head, broadest near anterior angles, distinctly tapering posteriad; lateral margins straight in posterior half (dorsal view); punctation moderately sparse and irregularly distributed, in antero-lateral portions with rather extensive impunctate patch on either side; midline broadly impunctate; lateral margins each with four long brown setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[794,1399,425,2081]" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[873,948,1321,1345]" captionStart="Figs 42–54" captionStartId="46.[189,229,2012,2034]" captionTargetBox="[191,1436,232,1943]" captionTargetId="figure-109@46.[189,1436,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figs 42–54: Forebody of Zyras spp.: kraatzi (42), exasperatus (43), pindarae (44), perforatus (45), championi (46), pallipes (47), condignus, holotype (48), condignus, Nepal (49), nigroaeneus (50), morvani (51), truncatus (52), longilobatus (53), hastatus (54). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742371/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">Fig. 43</figureCitation>
) 0.84 times as long as pronotum; punctation coarse, somewhat asperate or granulose in anterior half, rather dense near anterior margins and scutellum, moderately dense elsewhere. Hind wings probably present. Metatarsomere I approximately as long as the combined length of II–IV.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[794,1399,425,2081]" lastBlockId="10.[189,794,233,481]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="127" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">
Abdomen slightly narrower than elytra, with rather shallow anterior impressions on tergites III–V; anterior impressions of tergites III–V each with few scattered fine non-setiferous punctures in the middle, laterally impunctate; tergites III–IV with a lateral setiferous puncture on either side and with four setiferous punctures at posterior margins; tergite V with a lateral setiferous puncture on either side and with six setiferous punctures at posterior margin; tergite VI with a narrow transverse row of approximately ten non-setiferous punctures confined to the middle of anterior portion (laterally impunctate), with a lateral setiferous puncture on either side, and with six setiferous punctures at posterior margin; tergite VII with a narrow transverse band of non-setiferous punctures anteriorly, with a median pair of setiferous punctures at posterior fourth, and with a transverse series of six setiferous punctures near posterior margin, posterior margin with palisade fringe; tergite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[1303,1391,2057,2081]" captionStart="Figs 117–133" captionStartId="55.[151,191,2014,2036]" captionTargetBox="[159,1393,236,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-108@55.[151,1398,233,1972]" captionText="Figs 117–133: Zyras kraatzi (117–120), Z. exasperatus (121–124), Z. pindarae (125–131), and Z. perforatus (132–133): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (117–118, 121–122, 125–128, 132–133); male tergite VIII (119, 123, 130); male sternite VIII (120, 124, 131); paramere (129). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888364" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888364/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="126">Fig. 123</figureCitation>
) with 14 long black setae near posterior margin, posterior margin concavely excised in the middle, on either side of this concavity with a triangular projection.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,794,233,481]" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">
♂: sternite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[381,468,329,353]" captionStart="Figs 117–133" captionStartId="55.[151,191,2014,2036]" captionTargetBox="[159,1393,236,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-108@55.[151,1398,233,1972]" captionText="Figs 117–133: Zyras kraatzi (117–120), Z. exasperatus (121–124), Z. pindarae (125–131), and Z. perforatus (132–133): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (117–118, 121–122, 125–128, 132–133); male tergite VIII (119, 123, 130); male sternite VIII (120, 124, 131); paramere (129). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888364" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888364/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Fig. 124</figureCitation>
) with strongly convex posterior margin; median lobe of aedeagus 
<quantity box="[608,690,361,385]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="10" pageNumber="127" unit="mm" value="0.9">0.9 mm</quantity>
long and shaped as in 
<figureCitation box="[338,480,393,417]" captionStart="Figs 117–133" captionStartId="55.[151,191,2014,2036]" captionTargetBox="[159,1393,236,1954]" captionTargetId="figure-108@55.[151,1398,233,1972]" captionText="Figs 117–133: Zyras kraatzi (117–120), Z. exasperatus (121–124), Z. pindarae (125–131), and Z. perforatus (132–133): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (117–118, 121–122, 125–128, 132–133); male tergite VIII (119, 123, 130); male sternite VIII (120, 124, 131); paramere (129). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888364" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888364/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Figs 121–122</figureCitation>
; paramere nearly as long as median lobe, with rather short and slender apical lobe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,794,233,481]" box="[189,331,457,481]" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">♀: unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,794,521,1025]" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,402,521,545]" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Comparative notes</emphasis>
: Based on the external and sexual characters, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="SCHUBERT" authorityYear="1908" box="[313,463,554,577]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exasperatus">
<emphasis box="[313,463,554,577]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Z. exasperatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="SCHUBERT" authorityYear="1908" box="[692,793,553,577]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kraatzi">
<emphasis box="[692,793,553,577]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Z. kraatzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and allied species. It differs from the sympatric 
<taxonomicName authorityName="SCHUBERT" authorityYear="1908" box="[692,793,585,609]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kraatzi">
<emphasis box="[692,793,585,609]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Z. kraatzi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by larger body size, paler coloration (but note that the 
<typeStatus box="[189,286,649,673]" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">lectotype</typeStatus>
is teneral), longer and more slender antennae, a less convex pronotum (cross-section) with less sparse punctation, denser, coarser, and somewhat asperate or granulose punctation of the elytra, even fewer nonsetiferous punctures on the abdomen, and by the larger aedeagus with a slightly broader crista apicalis and a ventral process of slightly different shape.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,794,521,1025]" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">
The possibility that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2016" box="[393,499,874,897]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="iniquus">
<emphasis box="[393,499,874,897]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Z. iniquus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[559,650,873,897]" name="Pakistan" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Pakistan</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry name="Afghanistan" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Afghanistan</collectingCountry>
is conspecific with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="SCHUBERT" authorityYear="1908" box="[458,608,906,929]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exasperatus">
<emphasis box="[458,608,906,929]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Z. exasperatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cannot be ruled out completely. Mature males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="SCHUBERT" authorityYear="1908" box="[539,689,938,961]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="127" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exasperatus">
<emphasis box="[539,689,938,961]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Z. exasperatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
would be needed to assess intraspecific variation of coloration and other characters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="127" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="10.[189,794,1065,1185]" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,326,1065,1089]" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Distribution</emphasis>
: This species is currently known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[229,275,1098,1122]" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">type</typeStatus>
locality in Himalachal Pradesh, Northwest 
<collectingCountry box="[738,794,1097,1121]" name="India" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">India</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[196,265,1129,1153]" captionStart="Map 1" captionStartId="64.[189,234,822,843]" captionTargetBox="[189,1436,232,813]" captionTargetId="figure-76@64.[189,1436,232,813]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="Map 1: Revised distributions of Zyras kraatzi (black and white circles; white circle: type locality), Z. exasperatus (white circle), Z. iniquus (triangles), Z. pallipes (diamonds), and Z. championi (white stars) in the Himalaya." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742393" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742393/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Map 1</figureCitation>
). The previous record from 
<collectingRegion box="[565,701,1129,1153]" country="India" name="Uttarakhand" pageId="10" pageNumber="127">Uttarakhand</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="ASSING, V." pageId="10" pageNumber="127" pagination="87 - 175" refId="ref57174" refString="ASSING, V. 2016 a: A revision of Zyras STEPHENS sensu strictu of China, Taiwan, and Hong Kong, with records and (re-) descriptions of some species from other regions (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae: Lomechusini). - Stuttgarter Beitrage zur Naturkunde A, Neue Serie 9: 87 - 175." type="journal article" year="2016">ASSING 2016a</bibRefCitation>
) is based on a misidentification.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
